Animate a choropleth

Feasibility of a slider filter

John Little

2019-03-13

Backdrop: I spent several hours trying to use the crosstalk or plotly packages to generate a suitable choropleth with a slider filter. The purpose of the slider filter should enable filtering by year so the end-user can see change over time. In practice this proved to be unfeasible or unworkable. The animation transitions were sloppy or goofy; the slider wouldnt work as expected. In short the idea proved much easier than the execution.

However, the resulting investigation show me several aspects about the practical execution of showing change over time. I am shorthand documenting some of those issues here.

Load Library Packages

First, lets load the necessary packages.

library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(sf)
library(gganimate)

Get Data

Now lets get some ACS Census data and then scramble the data. By scramble what I mean is randomize the data so that its easier to see the changes over time. Since the data re scrambled, theres really no need to know what the actual census variable means, but Im pretty sure I started with population for North Carolina covering 2013 - 2016.

nc_2016 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2016")

nc_2015 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          year = 2015,
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2015")

nc_2014 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          year = 2014,
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2014")

nc_2013 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          year = 2013,
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2013")

Facet Map

Facet Maps are amazingly effective at showing change. Perhaps this is actually better than animating. Its certainly far less work using the facet_wrap() function. A benefit of a facet wrap is the ability to see all the data at one time. This makes comparisons across non-consecutive views easier to perceive.

ggplot(bg_r) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate, color = estimate)) +
  coord_sf(crs = 4326, datum = NA) +
  facet_wrap(~year)

Bar Plots

Sometimes geography is not the best way to showcase data, even when the data have a geographical element. The next plot visualizes the change over time for three counties in a side-by-side bar graph. The change over time is much more obvious when the yearly amount for relevant counties are positioned next to each other.

Side-by-side bar graphs are a ggplot option using position = "dodge".

A time-change question that is easier to answer with a bar graph than a choropleth is as follows: Which county has the highest annual amount for the year 2014?. Compare this question by looking at the choropleth facet map above and the bar graph below.

bg_r_nogeom %>% 
  mutate(county = str_extract(NAME, "\\w+")) %>% 
  filter(county == "Mecklenburg" | 
           county == "Durham" | 
           county == "Guilford") %>% 
  select(county, estimate, year) %>% 
  gather("foo", "year", -county, -estimate) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = county, y = estimate, fill = year), 
           position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d()

Highest County for 2014?

Animate

First the whole of North Carolina. This takes some CPU processing time.

p <- ggplot(bg_r) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate, color = estimate)) +
  coord_sf(datum = NA) +
  labs(title = '{next_expression}') +
  transition_filter(transition_length = 0.4, 
                    filter_length = 0.4,
                    year == "2013",
                    year == "2014",
                    year == "2015",
                    year == "2016") +
  enter_fade() +
  exit_fade() +
  shadow_mark(past = TRUE, future = TRUE)

animate(p)

Lets do a subset of counties. Its quicker. The main point of this animation is to transform the text label with the stringr package. It seems a bit overwrought but it works.

pcounty <- ggplot(bg_r_small) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate, color = estimate)) +
  coord_sf(datum = NA) +
  labs(title = "YEAR: {str_replace_all(str_replace(as.character(next_expression), 'year == ', ''), '\"', '')}") +
  transition_filter(transition_length = 0.4, 
                    filter_length = 0.4,
                    year == "2013",
                    year == "2014",
                    year == "2015",
                    year == "2016") +
  enter_fade() +
  exit_fade() +
  shadow_mark(past = TRUE, future = TRUE)


animate(pcounty)
